We are asked to “calculate the final tax payable item” (i.e. “Increase (Decrease) in Tax Payable”) based on the detailed transactions – that is, to “derive” by “adding up” the tax‐related amounts. (Typically a company on each sale records a “tax_amount” – a liability that, until remitted, appears as tax payable. In a cash‐flow “adjustments” section the “change in tax payable” is the net increase in that liability during the period.)

Looking briefly at the table we note that only the “Sale” transactions have a nonempty tax_amount value. (For example, one sale row has a tax_amount of 2803.89, another 9657.13, etc.) One then “sums” all of the tax_amount values on the sale transactions.

When one adds up (step‐by‐step summing the numbers as in the “calculation notes” below) these values come to

  356154.69

(This “grand‐total” is the net amount of tax collected during the period. If the beginning balance was zero and no tax payment entries appear in the dataset, the “increase in tax payable” will be this positive number.)

Thus, the final tax payable item (the “Increase in Tax Payable”) is 356154.69.
